'''Susan Peters''' (born '''Suzanne Carnahan'''; July 3, 1921{{spaced en dash}}October 23, 1952) was an American film, stage, and television actress who appeared in over twenty films over the course of her decade-long career. Though she began her career in uncredited and [[ingénue]] roles, she would establish herself as a serious dramatic actress in the mid-1940s.

Born in [[Spokane, Washington]], Peters was raised by her mother in [[Portland, Oregon]] and later, Los Angeles. Upon graduating from high school, she studied acting with Austrian theater director [[Max Reinhardt]], and signed a contract with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]. She appeared in numerous bit parts before earning a minor supporting role in ''[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]'' (1940). She made her last film for Warner Bros. in 1942, the film noir ''[[The Big Shot (1942 film)|The Big Shot]]'' opposite [[Humphrey Bogart]] and [[Richard Travis (actor)|Richard Travis]]; after its release, Warner opted not to renew her contract.

In 1942, Peters appeared in a supporting role in ''[[Tish (film)|Tish]]'', which resulted in her signing a contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] (MGM). The same year, she had a featured role in the [[Mervyn LeRoy]]-directed drama ''[[Random Harvest (film)|Random Harvest]]'', which earned her an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] and established her as a serious dramatic performer. Peters went on to appear as the lead in numerous films for MGM, including roles in the romantic comedy ''[[Young Ideas]]'' (1943), and several war films: ''[[Assignment in Brittany]]'' (1943), ''[[Song of Russia]]'' (1944), and ''[[Keep Your Powder Dry]]'' (1945).

On New Year's Day 1945, Peters's [[spinal cord]] was damaged from an accidental gunshot wound, leaving her permanently [[paraplegia|paraplegic]]. She returned to film portraying a wheelchair-bound villain in ''[[The Sign of the Ram]]'' (1948). Peters then transitioned to theater, appearing as Laura Wingfield in a critically acclaimed 1949 production of [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]'', which was slightly altered to allow Peters to perform in a wheelchair. She followed this with a production of ''[[The Barretts of Wimpole Street]]'', in which she portrayed crippled poet [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]]. By 1952, however, Peters had been suffering from [[Major depressive disorder|clinical depression]] for several years due to the dissolution of her marriage and her limited career options. In late 1952 she began [[starvation|starving]] herself, which combined with her paralysis led to chronic kidney infections and pneumonia. She died of ensuing health complications that year at age 31.

==Life and career==
===1921{{en dash}}1939: Early life===
Peters was born '''Suzanne Carnahan''' on July 3, 1921 in [[Spokane, Washington]], the elder of two children born to Robert and Abby Carnahan.{{sfn|Parish|2001|p=225}} Her father was a civil engineer of Irish descent, while her mother was of French descent, and a grand-niece of [[Robert E. Lee]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=176}} Peters had one younger brother, Robert Jr., born in 1923.{{sfn|Parish|2001|p=225}}{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=176}} Shortly after her birth, the Carnahan family moved to [[Portland, Oregon]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=176}}<ref name=tcm/> In 1928, her father was killed in a car accident in Portland,{{sfn|Parish|2001|p=225}} after which the family relocated to [[Seattle]], Washington,{{efn|U.S. Census data from 1930 lists Abby Carnahan a widow residing in [[Seattle]], [[King County, Washington]], with her daughter, Suzanne, and son, Robert.<ref name=abby>"United States Census, 1930," database with images, [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:XC3C-6YG FamilySearch] (accessed August 5, 2017), Abby Carnahan, Seattle, King, Washington, United States; citing enumeration district (ED) ED 108, sheet 23A, line 14, family 596, NARA microfilm publication T626 (Washington D.C.: National Archives and Records Administration, 2002), roll 2498; FHL microfilm 2,342,232.</ref>}} and later to [[Los Angeles]] to live with Peters' maternal French-born grandmother, Maria Patteneaude, a well-known dermatologist.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=176}}{{efn|An article published in ''The San Bernardino County Sun'' in January 1943 notes that Peters and her mother "came to Hollywood when Suzanne was still an infant."<ref name=sbcs>{{cite news|last1=Lowrance|first1=Dee|title=No Cinderella Girl -- Susan's Here to Stay|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3206439/the_san_bernardino_county_sun/|work=[[The San Bernardino Sun|The San Bernardino County Sun]]|location=San Bernardino, California|date=January 31, 1943|page=24|via =[[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = September 11, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref>}}

Peters was educated at Laird Hall School for Girls, the LaRue School in [[Azusa, California]], and [[Flintridge Sacred Heart Academy]] in Los Angeles.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} During her years in high school, she worked after hours in a Los Angeles department store, earning money to help support her mother and brother.<ref name=ht>{{cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Paul|title=Reviews and Previews|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3206521/harrisburg_telegraph/|work=Harrisburg Telegraph|date=February 17, 1943|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|location=Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|accessdate = September 11, 2015}} {{Open access}}</ref> Peters's mother supported herself and her two children by working in a dress shop and managing an apartment building.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} "We were poor but we managed, and we had fun," Peters recalled of her upbringing.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} She was an avid swimmer and tennis player, and also grew up riding horses; her talent as an equestrian allowed her to earn additional income by [[Horse training|breaking]] and showing other people's horses.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}}

Peters transferred to [[Hollywood High School]] during her senior year, and began taking drama classes in which she opted to enroll in place of cooking courses: "I took a drama course instead of a cooking course because I thought it was easier," Peters said. "Acting meant money, and [my family] needed money."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} While still in high school, she signed with a talent agent.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} She graduated from Hollywood High School in June 1939, along with [[Jason Robards]], [[Sheila Ryan]], and [[Dorothy Morris]] as members of her graduating class.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} With a newfound interest in acting, Peters earned a scholarship to the Max Reinhardt School of Dramatic Arts.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=178}} 

While performing in a showcase production of [[Philip Barry]]'s ''[[Holiday (play)|Holiday]]'' at the Reinhardt School,{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=178}} Peters was spotted by a talent scout for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] (MGM), who gave her a walk-on part in [[George Cukor]]'s ''[[Susan and God]]'' (1940).<ref>{{cite news|title=Dean Jagger Dominant in Religious Feature|author=Schallert, Edwin|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 20, 1940|p=A14}}</ref> During the shoot, Peters was reportedly so nervous that she fainted in front of the camera.<ref>{{cite news|title=Starlet Has 'Jitters'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 29, 1940|page=C2}}</ref> Despite her apprehension on set, Peters became a protégée of Cukor, who personally assigned her to private acting lessons with drama coach Gertrude Vogler.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=177–178}} Cukor believed Peters had star potential, but needed to not "talk through [her] nose."{{sfn|Parish|Bowers|1973|p=556}} He later recalled that she reminded him of "a young [[Katharine Hepburn]]. Not as aggressive as Kate, but that same finishing school appearance and drive."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}} 

===1940{{en dash}}1941: Contract with Warner Bros.===
[[File:Susan Peters 1941 portrait.jpg|thumb|upright=1|right|Peters in an early 1941 portrait for Warner Bros. as Suzanne Carnahan]]
In early 1940, Peters screen tested for [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]], who subsequently offered her a contract.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=178}} Then credited under her birth name, Suzanne Carnahan, Peters was cast in various small parts in Warner Bros. films; many these were uncredited bit parts or walk-on roles, such as in ''[[River's End (1940 film)|River's End]]'', ''[[The Man Who Talked Too Much]]'', ''[[Money and the Woman]]'', and ''[[Always a Bride]]'' (all released in 1940).{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=176–179}} She had her first credited role in the big-budget Western film ''[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]'' (1940), opposite [[Errol Flynn]], [[Olivia de Havilland]], and [[Rita Hayworth]]. In the film, Peters portrayed a young woman from [[Boston]] in love with a [[Kansas]] military officer.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=178}} During the [[Film promotion|press junket]]s to promote the film, Peters found interviews overwhelming, and later admitted: "I wasn't a good sport. I locked herself in my compartment during most of the trip."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=178}}

After ''Santa Fe Trail'', Peters had small roles in ''[[The Strawberry Blonde]]'', ''[[Meet John Doe]]'', ''[[Here Comes Happiness]]'' (1941), and ''[[Scattergood Pulls the Strings]]'' (all 1941), the latter of which earned her favorable reviews.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=179–180}} She then had a lead role as an [[ingénue]] in the comedy ''[[Three Sons o' Guns]]'' (1941), followed by a dramatic part playing the girlfriend of a convict in ''[[The Big Shot (1942 film)|The Big Shot]]'' (1942), opposite [[Richard Travis (actor)|Richard Travis]] and [[Humphrey Bogart]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=179–180}} She was also in shorts such as ''Young America Flies'' (1940) and ''Sockaroo'' (1941).<ref name=museum>{{cite news|title=Academy Starts Drive for Museum Collection|author= Schallert, Edwin|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 14, 1940|p=7}}</ref> At the urging of the studio (who initially suggested she change her name to Sharon O'Keefe), she dropped her birth name and took the stage name Susan Peters.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=177}}{{sfn|Parish|Bowers|1973|p=557}} By 1942, however, Warner Bros. chose not to renew her contract.<ref name=macpherson>{{cite news|work=St. Petersburg Times|page=11|location=St. Petersburg, Florida|series=Hollywood Roundup|title=Susan Peters Gave Herself 3 Years To Make Good--Did|author=MacPherson, Virginia|via=Google News|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19441206&id=96BPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wU4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7068,1430505|date=December 6, 1944}} {{free access}}</ref>

===1942{{en dash}}1944: Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer and critical success===
[[File:Susan Peters in Tish trailer.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1|Peters in the trailer for ''[[Tish (film)|Tish]]'' (1942)]]
Several months after being dropped by Warner Bros., Peters was contacted by MGM to test for a supporting role in the film ''[[Tish (film)|Tish]]'' (1942), a loose adaptation of a series of stories by [[Mary Roberts Rinehart]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=180}} She won the role and also signed a contract with the studio.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=180}} At the time, Peters was one of the most screen-tested actresses in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite book|title=Who's Who at Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|page=84|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hBEPAQAAMAAJ|publisher=Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|year=1944}}</ref> While filming ''Tish'', Peters met future husband, actor [[Richard Quine]], with whom she also starred in her second film with MGM, ''[[Dr. Gillespie's New Assistant]]'' (1942), alongside [[Van Johnson]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=180–181}} She and Peters later married on November 7, 1943 at Westwood Community Church in West Los Angeles.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=182}} 
[[File:Susan Peters and Van Johnson in Dr. Gillespie's Assistant.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|right|Peters and [[Van Johnson]] in ''[[Dr. Gillespie's New Assistant]]'' (1942)]]

After completing filming of the comedy ''[[Andy Hardy's Double Life]]'' (1942) in which she had a lead role,{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=181}} [[Mervyn LeRoy]] cast Peters in the drama ''[[Random Harvest (film)|Random Harvest]]'',{{sfn|Troyan|2010|p=139}}  in which she portrayed a young woman who falls in love with her step-uncle.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=181}} The film was one of the top 25 highest-earning films of the year,{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=181}} and Peters's performance garnered her critical acclaim, earning her an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name="toledo">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19890301&id=JnwUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-gIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4480,1513385|title=Susan Peters: A Look Back|date=March 1, 1989|work=[[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)|Toledo Blade]]|location=Toledo, Ohio|pages=P–3|accessdate=May 23, 2014|via=Google News}} {{free access}}</ref>

The success of ''Random Harvest'' led MGM to give Peters lead roles in other major pictures such as ''[[Assignment in Brittany]]'' (1943), in which she portrayed a French peasant girl.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=181}} This was followed with a minor but top-billed credit in the comedy ''[[Young Ideas]]'' (1943) with [[Herbert Marshall]] and [[Mary Astor]], directed by [[Jules Dassin]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=181}} She was subsequently cast as the female lead in ''[[Song of Russia]]'' (1943) opposite Robert Taylor.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=182}} The role earned her further critical acclaim, with a review in ''The Hollywood Reporter'' noting her as "a dramatic actress of the first rank."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=182}} The film however was controversial, as its portrayal of the [[Soviet Union]] was interpreted by some audiences and critics as being favorable and of a pro-[[Communism|Communist]] stance.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=182}} 

In early 1944, Peters was one of ten actors who were elevated from "featured player" status to the studio's official "star" category; the others included [[Esther Williams]], [[Laraine Day]], [[Kathryn Grayson]], Van Johnson, [[Margaret O'Brien]], [[Ginny Simms]], [[Robert Walker (actor, born 1918)|Robert Walker]], [[Gene Kelly]], and [[George Murphy]]. An official portrait taken of MGM's contracted players during this period prominently features Peters sharing the front row with the head of the studio himself, [[Louis B. Mayer]], and alongside such actors as [[James Stewart]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[Margaret Sullavan]], Katharine Hepburn, [[Hedy Lamarr]], and [[Greer Garson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/ostrow/tag/mgm-anniversary-photo/|work=Denver Post|title=Hollywood star-filled photos, then and now|series=Ostrow Off the Record|author=Ostrow, Joanne|date=March 3, 2014|accessdate= August 4, 2017}}</ref> In late 1944, Peters filmed ''[[Keep Your Powder Dry]]'', a war drama co-starring [[Lana Turner]] and [[Laraine Day]],<ref name=macpherson/> in which she portrayed the humble wife of a soldier.{{sfn|Basinger|1976|p=63}}

===1945{{en dash}}1950: Injury and career decline===
On January 1, 1945, Peters and husband Quine, along with his cousin and cousin's wife, went on a duck hunting trip in the [[Cuyamaca Mountains]] near San Diego.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=183}} At one point during the trip, Peters attempted to reach for a rifle, which accidentally discharged through her abdomen.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wfZPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=F1UDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5614,4185511&dq=susan+peters+shot&hl=en|title=Susan Peters Is Accidentally Shot|date= January 2, 1945|work=The Evening Independent|location=Massillon, Ohio|page=1|access-date=May 28, 2014|via=[[Google News]]}} {{free access}}</ref>{{sfn|Blottner|2015|p=202}} She was rushed to [[Scripps Mercy Hospital|Mercy Hospital]], roughly {{convert|65|mi|km}} away, and underwent emergency surgery.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=183}} The bullet damaged Peters's [[spinal cord]], leaving her permanently [[paraplegia|paralyzed from the waist down]], and she was required to use a wheelchair for the rest of her life.<ref name="ferrero">{{cite news|title=Actress Susan Peters, Paralyzed 7 Years, Dies|last=Ferrero|first=Lee|date=October 25, 1952|work=The Milwaukee Sentinel|location=Milwaukee, Wisconsin|page=3|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19521025&id=WWNQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fw8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5599,18206|via=Google News}} {{free access}}</ref> ''Keep Your Powder Dry'' premiered three months after the incident, on March 8, 1945.{{sfn|Nissen|2013|p=80}} Peters's mother, who had maintained a bedside vigil during her stay in the hospital, died nine months later in December 1945, which left Peters even more distraught.{{sfn|Parish|2001|p=226}} 

MGM continued to pay Peters a $100 weekly salary and medical expenses, but, unable to find suitable projects, she subsequently left the studio.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=183–184}} She later recalled: "Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer kept sending me [[Pollyanna]] scripts about crippled girls who were all sweetness and light, which I kept turning down. Two years after my accident, I gave up and broke my contract. I won't trade on my handicap."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} Among the projects offered to her were [[Joe Pasternak]] and [[Henry Koster]]'s ''[[The Unfinished Dance]]'' (1947), a remake of [[Jean Benoît-Lévy]]'s ''Ballerina''.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} In the film, Peters was offered the role of a ballerina who receives a spinal injury that leaves her unable to perform, but shed declined.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} Just prior to her injury, she had begun filming the drama ''The Outward Room''.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} The film's producers considered completing the project with stand-ins and refitting the script to allow Peters to appear in a wheelchair, but the project was ultimately shelved.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}}

[[File:Susan Peters driving (October 1947).jpg|thumb|upright=.9|left|Peters driving in October 1947; her vehicle was refitted with a hand-accelerator and brakes to allow her to drive after her paralysis]]
Upon leaving MGM, Peters was approached for numerous acting jobs on [[radio program]]s.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} She guest starred on a December 11, 1945 episode of ''[[Seventh Heaven (play)|Seventh Heaven]]'', opposite past film co-star Van Johnson.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} In 1946, Peters and husband Quine adopted a son, Timothy Richard.<ref name=tcm/> The same year, Peters made her first public appearance since her accident at [[Ciro's]] in West Hollywood, attending the debut of [[Desi Arnaz]] and His Orchestra along with her close friend [[Lucille Ball]].{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} Ball and Arnaz urged Peters to continue seeking acting work.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} Actor and friend [[Charles Bickford]] suggested that Peters option the novel ''The Sign of the Ram'' by Margaret Ferguson, which centers on a crippled woman who manipulates those around her.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=184}} Upon discussing the novel with her agent, Peters pitched the idea to [[Columbia Pictures]], who were enthusiastic about making a film adaptation.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=185}} 

Production on ''[[The Sign of the Ram]]'' began in July 1947 with director [[John Sturges]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46943918 |title=Susan Peters to return in new screen career |newspaper=[[The Australian Women's Weekly]]|volume=15 |issue=8 |location= Sydney, New South Wales |date=August 2, 1947 |access-date=April 21, 2017 |page=36 |via=[[Trove]]}} {{free access}}</ref> and Peters told reporters that she had never played a character "with the emotional range that this character has. It was a real challenge for me."{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=185}} The film's production was difficult, as Peters had to have either her mother or Quine on set to care for her son.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=185}} After production ended, Peters separated from Quine, claiming that he was cruel and would not speak to her for days at a time.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|pages=185–186}} Their divorce was finalized on September 10, 1948.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1338&dat=19480910&id=sfFXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vfUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4753,4195627|location=Spokane, Washington|title=Ex-Spokane Actress Susan Peters Cries As Divorce Granted|date=September 10, 1948|work=Spokane Daily Chronicle|page=1|access-date=May 28, 2014|via=Google News}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/50516034|work=The Courier-Mail|date=October 25, 1952|title=Cripple actress Susan Peters dead|page=1|location=Brisbane, Queensland, Australia|via=[[Trove]]}} {{free access}}</ref> ''The Sign of the Ram'' was released in March 1948, and critic [[Bosley Crowther]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the film an unfavorable review, writing: "The fortitude of Susan Peters in returning to the screen after a cruelly crippling accident, suffered three years ago, is worthy of a more substantial token of respect than it—and she—receives in ''The Sign of the Ram'', a Columbia picture which came to Loew's State yesterday. And the talents of several other actors of competence who are with her in this film are deserving of fuller protection against embarrassment than any of them get."<ref>{{cite news|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|author-link=Bosley Crowther|work=The New York Times|title='The Sign of the Ram,' Marking Return of Susan Peters to Films, at Loew's State|date= March 4, 1948|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?_r=1&res=9D07E6D71E3CE03ABC4C53DFB5668383659EDE&oref=slogin|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref> In light of her divorce and facing a lack of opportunity as an actress, Peters began suffering from chronic [[Major depressive disorder|depression]] at this time.<ref name=tcm/>

In 1949, she was cast as Laura in a touring stage production of ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]'' (reportedly with blessings from [[Tennessee Williams]]) which had its debut June 27, 1949, in [[Norwich, Connecticut]].<ref name=takesstage>{{cite news|title=Susan Peters Takes Stage In Wheelchair|work=[[The Blade (Toledo, Ohio)|Toledo Blade]]|date=June 27, 1949|access-date=December 28, 2016|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19490627&id=L1VIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FAAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7016,6159736|page=8|via=Google News|location=Toledo, Ohio}} {{free access}}</ref> The play was slightly altered under Williams's supervision in order for Peters to be allowed to perform the part in a wheelchair.<ref>{{cite news|title=Susan Peters in Play|publisher=United Press |work=The New York Times|date=June 27, 1949|page=18}}</ref> She received a standing ovation during the play's opening night, and the production toured throughout the East Coast.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=186}} The following year, in 1950, she was cast in a stage production of [[Rudolph Besier]]'s ''[[The Barretts of Wimpole Street]]'',{{sfn|Crespy|2013|p=63}}{{sfn|Blottner|2015|p=203}} playing the crippled poet [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]], which earned her positive critical reception among press.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19500124&id=ljAbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XU0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=2245,2793522|work=The Pittsburgh Press|title=Susan Peters Impressive in "Barretts" Revival|series=Show Shop|author=Monahan, Kaspar|date=January 24, 1950|page=8|access-date=July 30, 2017|via=Google News|location=Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania}} {{free access}}</ref> 

In March 1951, Peters signed onto the live [[NBC|NBC-TV]] television drama ''[[Miss Susan]]'',{{sfn|Parish|Bowers|1973|p=558}} in which she played an attorney confined to her wheelchair.{{sfn|McNeil|1991|p=506}}{{sfn|Erickson|2009|p=189}} Peters shot the series five days per week in Philadelphia from March 12 to December 28, 1951,{{sfn|Erickson|2009|p=189}} after which it was canceled when her health began to decline.<ref name="toledo"/><ref>{{cite news|title= Susan Peters Dies|work=The New York Times|date=October 25, 1952|p=17}}</ref>

===1951{{en dash}}1952: Health problems and death===
After the cancelation of ''Miss Susan'', she began a relationship with Robert Clark, a U.S. Colonel, and the two announced their engagement to be married; however, Clark broke off the engagement, which sent Peters into a deeper depression.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=187}} She relocated to [[Lemon Grove, California]], to live on her brother's cattle ranch, and her health began to steadily decline.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=187}} In mid-1952, she was admitted to a hospital in [[Exeter, California]] to undergo a [[skin graft]] procedure, after which she returned to her brother's home and lived in seclusion.{{Sfn|Crivello|1988|p=187}} She had plans to resume another touring stage production of ''The Barretts of Wimpole Street'' the following year, but her strength had dwindled and she struggled to put on weight.{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=187}}

In August 1952, Peters told her physician, Dr. Manchester: "I'm getting awfully tired. I think it possibly would be better if I did die."<ref>{{cite journal|work=[[National Board of Review#Films In Review|Films In Review]]|year=1976|volume=27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DRFCAQAAIAAJ&q=susan+peters+I’m+getting+awfully+tired.+I+think+it+would+be+better+if+I+did+die.%22&dq=susan+peters+I’m+getting+awfully+tired.+I+think+it+would+be+better+if+I+did+die.%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirkcad2b_VAhVL_mMKHYTlBzUQ6AEIKDAA|page=214|title=Susan Peters|publisher=National Board of Review of Motion Pictures|issn=0015-1688}}</ref> Over the following two months, she began [[starvation|starving herself]].<ref name=easy/><ref name=tcm/> Peters died on October 23, 1952 at Memorial Hospital in [[Visalia, California]] at the age of 31. Her doctor attributed her death to a chronic [[Pyelonephritis|kidney infection]], a complication caused by her paralysis, and [[pneumonia|bronchial pneumonia]].{{sfn|Crivello|1988|p=188}} He also noted that her death was hastened by self-induced dehydration and starvation because, in the last few weeks of her life, Peters had "lost interest" in eating and drinking and had lost the will to live.<ref name="ferrero"/><ref name=hr>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/race/oscars-sad-stories-9-acting-682163|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|title=Oscars: The Sad Stories of 9 Acting Nominees Who Committed Suicide|date=February 26, 2014|accessdate= August 5, 2017|author=Feinberg, Scott}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Susan Peters Dies; 'Lost Will' to Live|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=October 25, 1952|p=12}}</ref>

Her funeral was held on October 27 in [[Glendale, California]], after which she was buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park, Glendale|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]] next to her mother.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19521028&id=4pspAAAAIBAJ&sjid=A-YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6985,5113986|title=Actress' Rites Held Privately|date=October 28, 1952|location=Spokane, Washington|work=The Spokesman-Review|page=5|accessdate=May 28, 2014|via=Google News}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1981&dat=19521028&id=C4UkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tNkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6319,3990407|title=Susan Peters Buried|date=October 28, 1952|work=Beaver Valley Times|page=1|accessdate=May 28, 2014|via=Google News|location=Beaver, Pennsylvania}} {{free access}}</ref> At the time of her death Peters' son Timothy was living with her ex-husband. Her estate was worth $6,000 ({{Inflation|US|6000|1952|fmt=eq}}).<ref>{{cite news|title=Susan Peters' Estate Left to Former Husband|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 9, 1952|p=16}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Much of the public assessment and discussion of Peters has hinged on her paralysis and its impact on her life and career: Media historian [[Hal Erickson (author)|Hal Erickson]] considered Peters "one of Hollywood's most promising young actresses" of the 1940s, who "courageously attempted a comeback" despite her health problems.{{sfn|Erickson|2009|p=189}} Film scholar Gene Blottner similarly praised Peters as a "brilliant actress,"{{sfn|Blottner|2015|p=202}} as did John Charles of [[Turner Classic Movies]], who deemed her paralysis "one of the worst tragedies to affect the Hollywood acting community during the 1940s."<ref name=tcm>{{cite web|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|last=Charles|first=John|accessdate=August 14, 2018|title=Susan Peters Biography|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/151081%7C143413/Susan-Peters/}}</ref> For her contribution to motion pictures, Peters was posthumously<ref name=tcm/> awarded a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 1601 [[Vine Street]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/susan-peters/|title=Hollywood Star Walk: Susan Peters|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>

